Moreover, a calibration curve was drawn by plotting the relative fluorescence intensity of GA-CDs as a function of QLP concentration (0.25–60 μM) (Inset of Fig. 5c). It can be noticed that there is a good correlation coefficient between the relative emission intensity ratio I0/I and the concentration of QLP ranged from 0.25 to 60 µM, showing the the linear equation y = 0.3464x + 1.26, with a correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) of 0.9867, which favors to achieve the LOD of 0.00159 μM (1.59 nM) for QLP (LOD is estimated using 3σ/S, where “σ” denotes standard deviation and “S” signifies the slope of the linear calibration equation). As shown in Table 1
                        , GA-CDs-based approach for QLP detection is compared with other existing methods (HPTLC, GC–MS, immunoassays and metal and bimetallic nanocomposite-based analytical approaches). The GA-CDs-based fluorescence method exhibits several advantages (simplicity, rapidity, selectivity, eco-friendly and miniaturized analytical platform) as compared to reported analytical methods in the literature. Additionally, the analytical performance of GA-CDs integrated fluorescence method was compared with other analytical methods [34,36,37,39–44,26], demonstrating the developed method exhibited superior analytical performance with regard to selectivity, sensitivity and sample preparations for QLP assay.
